Brexit, and what next?
NEW YORK – It will take a lot of time for Britain, Europe, and the entire world to digest the implications of the referendum on « Brexit » conducted by the United Kingdom.
The most profound consequences will depend, of course, on the European Union's response to the UK's withdrawal.
Most people initially believed that the EU would not « cut the branch on which it is sitting »: after all, a friendly divorce seems to be in everyone's interest.
But the divorce – as is often the case – could become complicated.
The advantages of commercial and economic integration between the United Kingdom and the EU are mutual, and if the EU took seriously its conviction that greater economic integration is desirable, its leaders would seek to ensure that ties remain as close as possible given the circumstances.
However, Jean-Claude Juncker, the architect of massive tax avoidance schemes benefiting companies in Luxembourg and now President of the European Commission, seems to be taking a hard line: "Out means out," he declared.
This instinctive reaction may be understandable, given that Juncker could be seen as the one who presided over the first stage of the EU's dissolution.
He argues that, in order to deter other countries from leaving, the EU must not accept any compromise, offering the UK barely more than what is guaranteed by the agreements of the World Trade Organization.
In other words, Europe must not be kept united by the benefits it offers its members, which far exceed its costs.
Economic prosperity, a sense of solidarity, and pride in being European are not enough, according to Juncker.
No, Europe must be maintained by threats, intimidation, and fear.
This position does not take into account a lesson that appears clearly, both in the vote in favor of Brexit and in the primaries of the Republican Party in the United States: a large part of the population has suffered greatly in recent times.
The neoliberal agenda of the last four decades may have been good for the top 1%, but not for the rest of the population.
I had predicted for a long time that this stagnation would eventually have political consequences.
This day has now arrived.
On both sides of the Atlantic, citizens consider trade agreements to be the source of their misfortunes.
Although this is an excessive simplification, it is understandable.
Today's trade agreements are negotiated in secret, ensuring good representation of corporate interests but completely excluding ordinary citizens or workers.
No surprise, the results have been one-sided: the bargaining position of workers has weakened further, thereby exacerbating the effects of legislation that reduces the power of unions and workers' rights.
Although trade agreements have played a role in creating these inequalities, many other factors have contributed to tipping the political balance in favor of capital.
Intellectual property rules, for example, have increased the power of pharmaceutical companies to raise prices.
However, any increase in the market power of companies implies de facto a decrease in real wages – an increase in inequalities that has become a characteristic of most advanced countries today.
In many sectors, industrial concentration is increasing – and so is market power.
The effects of stagnation and the decrease in real wages have added to those of austerity, which has threatened cuts in public services on which so many low- and middle-income workers depend.
The resulting economic uncertainty for workers, when combined with migration, has created a toxic mix.
Many refugees are victims of wars and oppression to which the West has contributed.
Providing aid is a moral responsibility for all, but especially for former colonial powers.
And yet, although many would probably deny it, an increase in the supply of unskilled labor leads – as long as we are in the presence of normal negatively sloped demand curves – to a decrease in equilibrium wages.
And when wages cannot decrease, unemployment increases.
This is especially concerning in countries where poor economic management has already led to a high level of overall unemployment.
Europe, particularly the eurozone, has been very poorly managed over the past few decades, to the point that its average unemployment rate is now in double digits.
Unfettered migration into Europe means that countries which have more successfully reduced unemployment will inevitably end up hosting more than their fair share of refugees.
The workers in these countries bear the cost of depressed wages and higher unemployment, while employers benefit from cheaper labor.
As expected, the burden of refugees is borne by those least able to bear it.
Of course, there is a lot of talk about the net benefits of immigration.
For a country offering a low level of guaranteed benefits – social protection, education, health care etc. – to all its citizens, this can be the case.
But, for countries that provide a decent social safety net, the opposite is true.
The result of all this downward pressure on wages and cuts in public services has been the erosion of the middle class, with similar consequences on both sides of the Atlantic.
Middle-class and working-class households have not benefited from economic growth.
They understand that banks caused the 2008 crisis; but they then saw billions allocated to bailing out banks, and insignificant amounts to save their homes and jobs.
While the real median income (adjusted for inflation) for a full-time male worker in the United States is lower than it was four decades ago, the electorate's anger should come as no surprise.
Moreover, politicians who promised change did not meet expectations.
Ordinary citizens knew the system was unfair, but they began to see it as even more rigged than they had imagined, thereby losing the little confidence they still had in the ability or willingness of traditional politicians to correct it.
This is also understandable: the new politicians shared the perspectives of those who had promised that globalization would be beneficial for all.
However, a vote of anger does not solve problems, and can instead lead to a political and economic situation that is even worse.
The same applies if one responds to a vote with anger.
Forgetting the past is a basic principle in economics.
On both sides of the Channel, politics must now seek to understand how, in a democracy, the political establishment could have done so little to address the concerns of many citizens.
Each EU government must now consider improving the well-being of ordinary citizens as its main objective.
More neoliberal ideology will not help.
And we should stop confusing goals and means: for example, free trade, if well managed, could bring greater shared prosperity; but if poorly managed, it will certainly reduce the standard of living of many – perhaps even the majority – of citizens.
There are alternatives to the current neoliberal arrangements that can create shared prosperity, just as there are alternatives – such as the proposed Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership with the EU by American President Barack Obama – that would cause much more harm.
The challenge today is to learn from the past, in order to adopt the former and avoid the latter.
